00:01:06.877 --> 00:01:12.060
ITAMAR SIMONSON: Thank you,
and thanks for your patience.

00:01:12.060 --> 00:01:15.350
Today we would like to talk
about consumer decision making

00:01:15.350 --> 00:01:17.590
in the age of nearly
perfect information.

00:01:17.590 --> 00:01:20.710
But before we get there,
let's take a moment

00:01:20.710 --> 00:01:24.630
to talk about what we used
to believe about consumers.

00:01:24.630 --> 00:01:27.330
In the beginning, the assumption
was that consumers are

00:01:27.330 --> 00:01:31.280
generally rational, but because
they cannot tell the quality

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:34.500
of things, marketers
can influence them using

00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:37.980
advertising, and branding,
and building loyalty,

00:01:37.980 --> 00:01:40.680
and all those other things
that you might have read

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:42.910
in marketing textbooks.

00:01:42.910 --> 00:01:46.280
Then about 30 years ago, it
got a little more interesting.

00:01:46.280 --> 00:01:49.860
And more and more
studies that we have done

00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:53.090
have shown that
consumers often make

00:01:53.090 --> 00:01:55.410
decisions that are irrational.

00:01:55.410 --> 00:02:01.070
By irrational, contrary to the
common concept or conception

00:02:01.070 --> 00:02:03.950
of irrationality, what
we mean by irrationality

00:02:03.950 --> 00:02:07.210
is that we violate
assumptions of economics.

00:02:07.210 --> 00:02:09.740
People do not maximize utility.

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:11.660
And sometimes they
choose a over b.

00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:15.170
Other times they
choose b over a,

00:02:15.170 --> 00:02:17.771
even though it's
the same a and b.

00:02:20.717 --> 00:02:26.490
I spent the first 20, 25
years of my career working

00:02:26.490 --> 00:02:29.280
on the irrationality
of consumers.

00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:32.745
This is an article that
I published back in 1994

00:02:32.745 --> 00:02:36.560
in the New York Times, and I
think the title of the article

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:41.650
tells you what it was about and
who I thought was in control.

00:02:41.650 --> 00:02:44.470
Let me just give you
a couple of examples

00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:48.470
of effects,
irrationality effects.

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:53.100
So in this particular
study, we showed one group

00:02:53.100 --> 00:02:56.179
of consumers those
two microwave ovens.

00:02:56.179 --> 00:02:57.470
We asked them to make a choice.

00:02:57.470 --> 00:03:01.300
You see there is one that's the
Amazon that's less expensive,

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:03.410
and a Panasonic
that's more expensive.

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:08.200
Both of them are 35%
off the regular price.

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:11.680
A second group of
consumers chose

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:14.460
among three microwave ovens.

00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:18.100
You note that the top one is
the same one that we saw before.

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:20.980
The bottom one is the same
one that we saw before.

00:03:20.980 --> 00:03:26.280
But now there's a third option,
which is another Panasonic.

00:03:26.280 --> 00:03:28.950
It's even more expensive,
has more features,

00:03:28.950 --> 00:03:32.230
but it's only 10% off.

00:03:32.230 --> 00:03:32.830
OK.

00:03:32.830 --> 00:03:34.480
What did we find?

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:36.920
We found that
consumers were more

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:41.550
likely to choose the Panasonic
over the Amazon in this group

00:03:41.550 --> 00:03:44.260
than in the other group,
even though we added

00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:48.260
another Panasonic
to the choices.

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:51.470
That's known as the
asymmetric dominance effect,

00:03:51.470 --> 00:03:56.845
because this Panasonic is
dominated by this Panasonic.

00:03:59.420 --> 00:04:02.160
Since then, those effects
have been shown many times.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:06.860
Now a year ago, a doctoral
student at Stanford,

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:09.790
[INAUDIBLE] and I,
tried to replicate

00:04:09.790 --> 00:04:14.100
the asymmetric dominance effect,
except that, in this case,

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:17.500
we provided consumers,
or participants

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:19.440
in the study,
additional information.

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:22.890
The kind of information
that you receive today

00:04:22.890 --> 00:04:27.190
when you go to shop on
Google Shopping, or Amazon,

00:04:27.190 --> 00:04:28.980
or any other website.

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:30.420
We showed them some reviews.

00:04:30.420 --> 00:04:31.860
We showed them other options.

00:04:31.860 --> 00:04:36.600
We showed them more detailed
specifications, and so on.

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:41.190
So some people chose between
these two paper shredders,

00:04:41.190 --> 00:04:46.206
and other respondents saw
these three shredders.

00:04:46.206 --> 00:04:48.580
And you don't see here all
the information they received.

00:04:48.580 --> 00:04:51.780
As I said, they received a
great deal more information.

00:04:51.780 --> 00:04:53.050
What did we find?

00:04:53.050 --> 00:04:57.120
We found that now, the
asymmetric dominance effect

00:04:57.120 --> 00:05:00.000
was gone.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.020
Consumers no longer
made a choice

00:05:04.020 --> 00:05:07.660
on the basis of comparing
the options in front of them.

00:05:07.660 --> 00:05:10.950
Instead, they took advantage
of all the other information

00:05:10.950 --> 00:05:12.880
we presented to them.

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:17.370
As we will explain later,
we would connect it

00:05:17.370 --> 00:05:21.780
to a broader phenomenon
whereby consumers are much less

00:05:21.780 --> 00:05:27.040
likely to make judgment relative
to the options you show them

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:29.590
and relative to all
kinds of other things,

00:05:29.590 --> 00:05:32.520
like other products
by the same brand.

00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:36.270
And instead, they evaluate
each product individually.

00:05:36.270 --> 00:05:40.550
So this is a really fundamental
change in decision making.

00:05:40.550 --> 00:05:42.500
Let me give you another example.

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:45.100
This is something to do
with frequency programs.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:50.000
This is based on a study that
Ran Kivetz, who at the time

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:51.575
was a doctoral
student at Stanford

00:05:51.575 --> 00:05:54.540
and is now a professor
of marketing at Columbia.

00:05:54.540 --> 00:06:01.270
So we looked here at whether
participants-- they didn't even

00:06:01.270 --> 00:06:03.430
know they were
participating in a study--

00:06:03.430 --> 00:06:06.100
would sign up for
this loyalty program.

00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:08.750
So we told them-- these
were students at Columbia--

00:06:08.750 --> 00:06:11.600
we said, if you
join this program,

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:17.980
after you buy twelve sandwiches
in any food place on campus,

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:21.470
at the end of the day you'll
get two free movie tickets.

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:28.540
A second group of
participants were

00:06:28.540 --> 00:06:33.300
told that if they buy 12
sandwiches and they also

00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:39.030
by 12 orders of sushi, they
will, at the end of the day,

00:06:39.030 --> 00:06:41.990
get two free movie tickets.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:44.117
Now, which program
is more attractive?

00:06:44.117 --> 00:06:44.700
The first one.

00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:48.890
This one requires you to
buy 12 sandwiches and also

00:06:48.890 --> 00:06:53.460
12 orders of sushi
for the same reward.

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:55.380
Now we asked all
of the participants

00:06:55.380 --> 00:06:57.880
about the kinds of food
they like and dislike

00:06:57.880 --> 00:07:00.010
so we could identify
the segments

00:07:00.010 --> 00:07:03.660
of what we called sushi lovers.

00:07:03.660 --> 00:07:06.510
For those, what
we found was they

00:07:06.510 --> 00:07:12.500
were more likely to join this
program than the other program.

00:07:12.500 --> 00:07:13.040
Why?

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:16.580
We call that the idiosyncratic
[? futuristic. ?] What

00:07:16.580 --> 00:07:20.860
we're saying is that people
really cannot assess the value

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:26.050
of a program or how you
translate effort to reward.

00:07:26.050 --> 00:07:29.050
Instead what they do,
they assess the reward

00:07:29.050 --> 00:07:31.390
relative to the
effort that it would

00:07:31.390 --> 00:07:34.630
require from other participants.

00:07:34.630 --> 00:07:37.560
And they say to themselves,
I really like sushi.

00:07:37.560 --> 00:07:38.735
I buy sushi anyway.

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:45.730
Relative to others this
is more attractive for me.

00:07:45.730 --> 00:07:48.440
And as a result, those
people who like sushi

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:53.870
were more likely to prefer
the frequency program that

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:59.315
required you to buy both
12 sandwiches and 12

00:07:59.315 --> 00:08:00.430
orders of sushi.

00:08:00.430 --> 00:08:03.840
That's another example
of making decisions

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:06.610
relative to other
things, in this case,

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:11.400
relative to other consumers.

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:16.240
This is, what Cliff mentioned,
the compromise effect.

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:18.540
So what I worked
on many years ago,

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:21.200
about 30 years ago
for my dissertation,

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:24.890
I looked at what I later
called the compromise effect.

00:08:24.890 --> 00:08:27.990
So some participants in
the study, in this case,

00:08:27.990 --> 00:08:30.100
chose between two cameras.

00:08:30.100 --> 00:08:34.409
That's actually from a
study done later in 1990.

00:08:34.409 --> 00:08:40.059
And you see there are two
models of Minolta, which

00:08:40.059 --> 00:08:41.520
those if you who
are old remember

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:46.190
there was such a brand, and
different number of features

00:08:46.190 --> 00:08:48.450
and different price level.

00:08:48.450 --> 00:08:51.960
Other people choose
among three cameras.

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:55.980
You know that the first two
are the same as those before,

00:08:55.980 --> 00:08:59.480
but now there is another one
that has even more features

00:08:59.480 --> 00:09:01.960
and is more expensive.

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:04.950
Well, what did we find?

00:09:04.950 --> 00:09:13.070
We found that most consumers
shifted to the middle option.

00:09:13.070 --> 00:09:17.200
The big loser was
the cheapest option.

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:23.060
And there was a general tendency
of people to go, to converge,

00:09:23.060 --> 00:09:26.020
on the middle option
in a given set.

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:28.900
Again this relative
decision making.

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:29.770
Why?

00:09:29.770 --> 00:09:32.490
Because it means that you
are not basing your decision

00:09:32.490 --> 00:09:37.340
on the quality and value
of the particular option.

00:09:37.340 --> 00:09:41.240
Instead, you're looking
at other options.

00:09:41.240 --> 00:09:44.720
And on that basis you
make your decision.

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:50.990
Again, last year we tried
to replicate this effect,

00:09:50.990 --> 00:09:55.670
and we used again cameras,
different cameras, same design.

00:09:58.300 --> 00:10:01.090
And as I said earlier, we
provided more information.

00:10:01.090 --> 00:10:05.700
We also gave them reviews, and
we got them specifications,

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:08.340
and additional information,
the kind of information

00:10:08.340 --> 00:10:10.780
you easily obtain today.

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:13.260
The compromise effect was gone.

00:10:13.260 --> 00:10:15.970
Now the significance
of this effect

00:10:15.970 --> 00:10:19.295
goes far beyond the compromise
effect and the other effects

00:10:19.295 --> 00:10:21.150
that I talked about.

00:10:21.150 --> 00:10:26.420
It means that there is a general
trend that Emanuel and I are

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:33.200
calling the shift from relative
to absolute decision making.

00:10:33.200 --> 00:10:38.030
If you think about it, suppose
you were buying a laptop back

00:10:38.030 --> 00:10:40.280
in '99.

00:10:40.280 --> 00:10:44.170
You might have based your
decision on the brand,

00:10:44.170 --> 00:10:46.450
on where it was made.

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:49.680
You might have used
some general rule,

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:52.140
such as you get
what you pay for.

00:10:52.140 --> 00:10:57.510
These are all relative
proxies or quality proxies.

00:10:57.510 --> 00:10:58.170
Why?

00:10:58.170 --> 00:11:00.200
Because you compare
this product that you're

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:03.860
thinking of buying to other
products by the same brand,

00:11:03.860 --> 00:11:07.200
other products of the same
price level, and other products

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:10.190
in the same country
of origin, and so on.

00:11:10.190 --> 00:11:14.960
You're not making your decision
on the basis of your evaluation

00:11:14.960 --> 00:11:18.670
of the quality of this
particular product.

00:11:18.670 --> 00:11:21.940
Now the problem
with quality proxies

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:23.590
is that they're
often inaccurate,

00:11:23.590 --> 00:11:27.990
because some brands make good
products and bad products.

00:11:27.990 --> 00:11:33.160
And that's true for all kinds
of other quality proxies.

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:35.370
Now what has changed?

00:11:35.370 --> 00:11:38.560
These are just a few of
the sources of information

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:41.600
that you have today to
assess the real value

00:11:41.600 --> 00:11:45.130
of each individual product.

00:11:45.130 --> 00:11:47.540
It means that today
you don't have

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:52.220
to rely on relative proxies.

00:11:52.220 --> 00:11:58.090
Instead, you can evaluate
each product individually.

00:11:58.090 --> 00:12:01.380
Now this is a very
important change.

00:12:01.380 --> 00:12:06.670
If you think about if you've
ever taken a marketing course

00:12:06.670 --> 00:12:08.750
or read any marketing
textbook, you

00:12:08.750 --> 00:12:12.120
know that much of what
we teach in marketing

00:12:12.120 --> 00:12:18.590
is about the creation of quality
proxies, how to build brands,

00:12:18.590 --> 00:12:22.720
how to create customer
loyalty, all of those things

00:12:22.720 --> 00:12:31.250
that represent quality proxies,
or relative quality proxies.

00:12:31.250 --> 00:12:34.410
And we say that they are
becoming, in many product

00:12:34.410 --> 00:12:37.980
categories, much less important.

00:12:37.980 --> 00:12:40.930
Now let's simplify
and talk about what

00:12:40.930 --> 00:12:44.250
are the main forces
that influence

00:12:44.250 --> 00:12:46.520
consumer decision making.

00:12:46.520 --> 00:12:51.480
One, we call O. O stands for
what you learn from others.

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:55.040
For example, a friend
of yours tells you

00:12:55.040 --> 00:12:58.560
about a good restaurant
or a good movie, that

00:12:58.560 --> 00:13:04.340
would be an example of O.
P is what's in your head

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:10.280
from prior experience,
what you were born with,

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:13.040
your family background,
what you've done before,

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:16.740
anything already
stored in your head.

00:13:16.740 --> 00:13:20.530
We call that P, or prior.

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:24.740
And the third one is M, which
is the influence of marketers,

00:13:24.740 --> 00:13:27.520
advertising, brands, and so on.

00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:31.510
These three sources
of information

00:13:31.510 --> 00:13:37.890
together influence what you know
and how you evaluate products.

00:13:37.890 --> 00:13:42.180
If you want a summary of what
has happened in the past 10,

00:13:42.180 --> 00:13:51.580
15 years, it's the rise
in the impact of O,

00:13:51.580 --> 00:13:55.950
through reviews, with the
easy access to expert reviews,

00:13:55.950 --> 00:13:59.610
social media, and so on.

00:13:59.610 --> 00:14:06.290
At the expense, primarily,
of marketers, of M.

00:14:06.290 --> 00:14:10.370
Because if you can assess
the quality of each product

00:14:10.370 --> 00:14:12.930
individually, you're
less likely to rely

00:14:12.930 --> 00:14:15.940
on what marketers are telling
you about the product.

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:18.870
And as we know, they
have their own interest

00:14:18.870 --> 00:14:22.340
to promote those products.

00:14:22.340 --> 00:14:26.440
So one thing to
think about it, is

00:14:26.440 --> 00:14:29.190
what we call the O continuum.

00:14:29.190 --> 00:14:36.720
And what we're saying is
that the degree to which O

00:14:36.720 --> 00:14:42.780
influences consumer decisions
is a function of the product

00:14:42.780 --> 00:14:43.990
category.

00:14:43.990 --> 00:14:47.600
So there are some products--
before you buy a Snickers bar

00:14:47.600 --> 00:14:50.910
or before you buy paper
clips, you probably

00:14:50.910 --> 00:14:53.460
are not going to
bother to read reviews.

00:14:53.460 --> 00:14:55.750
On the other hand,
before you buy cameras

00:14:55.750 --> 00:14:58.660
you may very well will.

00:14:58.660 --> 00:15:00.700
It also varies by segment.

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:03.480
Some consumers are
more likely to look

00:15:03.480 --> 00:15:04.940
for reviews than others.

00:15:04.940 --> 00:15:06.540
It also depends on context.

00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:11.740
If you buy a product on
a website like Amazon,

00:15:11.740 --> 00:15:16.130
like it or not, you'll
be staring at reviews,

00:15:16.130 --> 00:15:18.960
so therefore they are
likely to influence you.

00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:23.830
So there are different factors
that determine the impact of O

00:15:23.830 --> 00:15:25.870
on your decisions.

00:15:25.870 --> 00:15:31.940
The rest of our talk will
focus on this end, which

00:15:31.940 --> 00:15:37.250
is all of those categories and
situations where consumers make

00:15:37.250 --> 00:15:42.380
decisions largely based on
O, on what others are saying,

00:15:42.380 --> 00:15:45.660
consumers and experts.

00:15:45.660 --> 00:15:49.460
Well now quickly we'll review
some of the key marketing

00:15:49.460 --> 00:15:52.670
mantras, or the key
marketing principles, that

00:15:52.670 --> 00:15:54.690
are influenced by
this shift from

00:15:54.690 --> 00:15:58.850
relative to absolute
decision making.

00:15:58.850 --> 00:16:02.370
Let's start with branding.

00:16:02.370 --> 00:16:07.270
And there's probably nothing
more marketing than branding.

00:16:07.270 --> 00:16:11.510
And this is the
topic where we are

00:16:11.510 --> 00:16:15.780
saying all kinds of
surprising things in the book,

00:16:15.780 --> 00:16:18.760
among other things, this
notion that consumers

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:21.500
are becoming a
little more rational.

00:16:21.500 --> 00:16:25.490
Even though nowadays there's
a lot more talk about consumer

00:16:25.490 --> 00:16:27.850
irrationality there's
really nothing

00:16:27.850 --> 00:16:31.460
that generated greater
response then this notion

00:16:31.460 --> 00:16:33.930
that brands in many
product categories

00:16:33.930 --> 00:16:37.580
are becoming less
important, especially as

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:40.250
indicators of quality.

00:16:40.250 --> 00:16:42.810
Some people, in fact are
saying that, if anything,

00:16:42.810 --> 00:16:45.890
brands are becoming
more important.

00:16:45.890 --> 00:16:46.720
Why?

00:16:46.720 --> 00:16:48.810
They say, well there's
so much information

00:16:48.810 --> 00:16:51.930
out there on the
internet that consumers

00:16:51.930 --> 00:16:54.910
experience information overload.

00:16:54.910 --> 00:16:59.450
And as a result, what they have
to do, they just go by brand.

00:16:59.450 --> 00:17:03.020
This argument assumes
that consumers

00:17:03.020 --> 00:17:04.230
have just two options.

00:17:04.230 --> 00:17:07.250
Either you process all
the information out there,

00:17:07.250 --> 00:17:08.667
or you go by brands.

00:17:08.667 --> 00:17:10.250
Of course, in reality,
there are a lot

00:17:10.250 --> 00:17:12.673
of good intermediate solutions.

00:17:12.673 --> 00:17:14.589
You don't have to process
all the information.

00:17:14.589 --> 00:17:17.290
In fact, you can make
very good decisions

00:17:17.290 --> 00:17:21.089
and get a great deal of
information in a few seconds.

00:17:21.089 --> 00:17:26.069
And I'll illustrate
that in a second.

00:17:26.069 --> 00:17:27.565
Let's think about restaurants.

00:17:30.110 --> 00:17:33.580
In the past, chain restaurants
had a significant advantage,

00:17:33.580 --> 00:17:37.460
because you knew what you were
getting regardless of location,

00:17:37.460 --> 00:17:40.230
even if, for example,
you were out of town.

00:17:40.230 --> 00:17:44.430
However, think about
nowadays if you're

00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:47.030
looking for information
about individual restaurants.

00:17:47.030 --> 00:17:48.550
This particular
one is a restaurant

00:17:48.550 --> 00:17:51.640
from Seattle, Machiavelli.

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:56.060
If you're interested
in Machiavelli,

00:17:56.060 --> 00:17:58.280
you get over 400 reviews.

00:17:58.280 --> 00:18:03.840
You get over 50 pictures,
photos of various dishes.

00:18:03.840 --> 00:18:05.790
You have a great
deal of information.

00:18:05.790 --> 00:18:08.150
It doesn't take a
whole lot of effort

00:18:08.150 --> 00:18:14.150
to get an idea of how good and
how popular this restaurant is.

00:18:14.150 --> 00:18:17.200
And if you like to read a
little bit of the reviews,

00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:19.170
you quickly see that
one of the issues

00:18:19.170 --> 00:18:20.840
there is that there
are long lines

00:18:20.840 --> 00:18:24.090
and they don't
take reservations.

00:18:24.090 --> 00:18:29.610
So as we can see,
this new environment

00:18:29.610 --> 00:18:35.190
increases the power of
independent restaurants

00:18:35.190 --> 00:18:37.170
at the expense of
chain restaurants.

00:18:37.170 --> 00:18:41.000
Indeed, a study conducted
might by Michael Luca

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:42.340
established that's the case.

00:18:42.340 --> 00:18:46.580
That as Yelp penetrated the
Seattle market, the revenues

00:18:46.580 --> 00:18:49.670
of independent
restaurants increased

00:18:49.670 --> 00:18:53.018
at the expense of
chain restaurants.

00:18:53.018 --> 00:18:54.643
Now this has far
reaching implications.

00:18:58.040 --> 00:19:02.260
For example, it means
that the entry barriers

00:19:02.260 --> 00:19:05.950
to many categories
are declining.

00:19:05.950 --> 00:19:10.900
As long as you have
a good product,

00:19:10.900 --> 00:19:14.240
you have a chance
of being successful.

00:19:14.240 --> 00:19:16.710
Think about this
computer that we

00:19:16.710 --> 00:19:19.375
brought here and
didn't work by Asus.

00:19:19.375 --> 00:19:20.500
EMANUEL ROSEN: It did work.

00:19:20.500 --> 00:19:21.600
ITAMAR SIMONSON: It did work.

00:19:21.600 --> 00:19:22.433
EMANUEL ROSEN: Yeah.

00:19:22.433 --> 00:19:24.210
ITAMAR SIMONSON: I take it back.

00:19:24.210 --> 00:19:31.620
Asus used to make components
for other PC manufacturers,

00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:33.590
but at some point
their CEO decided

00:19:33.590 --> 00:19:36.650
to sell directly to consumers
under the name of Asus.

00:19:36.650 --> 00:19:39.570
People told him, you're
not going to be successful,

00:19:39.570 --> 00:19:41.680
because no one knows
your name, and you'll

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:44.350
need to spend a lot of
money on advertising.

00:19:44.350 --> 00:19:49.280
But he thought that he has a
way of doing it successfully.

00:19:49.280 --> 00:19:52.960
He just sold a good product
that got excellent reviews

00:19:52.960 --> 00:19:53.840
on the internet.

00:19:53.840 --> 00:19:57.580
Some of you may
remember the Eee PC.

00:19:57.580 --> 00:20:01.270
And indeed, it became
very successful.

00:20:01.270 --> 00:20:06.030
And nowadays Asus
is in the top five

00:20:06.030 --> 00:20:10.245
in categories such as
laptops and tablets.

00:20:13.020 --> 00:20:17.430
It also means that
previously unknown names

00:20:17.430 --> 00:20:20.720
can establish themselves
as leaders in the category.

00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:23.490
You may be familiar with the
recent acquisition of Google

00:20:23.490 --> 00:20:26.830
called Nest, and
some of you are also

00:20:26.830 --> 00:20:30.480
familiar with Roku, which
is one of the leaders

00:20:30.480 --> 00:20:34.810
in the video streaming category.

00:20:34.810 --> 00:20:38.940
Previously unknown names
have become very popular.

00:20:38.940 --> 00:20:41.675
It shows you that when
brands are less important,

00:20:41.675 --> 00:20:46.890
and each product is evaluated
independently, then even

00:20:46.890 --> 00:20:51.940
no-names have a chance of
establishing themselves,

00:20:51.940 --> 00:20:53.780
as long as they have
the right product that

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:56.110
gets the right reviews.

00:20:56.110 --> 00:21:00.560
It also means that it's
easier to diversify.

00:21:00.560 --> 00:21:02.940
Now in the past, we used
to teach our MBA students

00:21:02.940 --> 00:21:06.920
that each brand is associated
with certain perceived skills,

00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:11.960
so therefore, you should stay
in your area of expertise.

00:21:11.960 --> 00:21:15.680
But that's no longer true,
because if each product is

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:18.490
evaluated
independently, it means

00:21:18.490 --> 00:21:24.280
that you can be in all kinds of
categories like LG and Samsung.

00:21:24.280 --> 00:21:26.540
And as long as you make
the right products,

00:21:26.540 --> 00:21:30.440
consumers will accept it.

00:21:30.440 --> 00:21:31.190
EMANUEL ROSEN: Hi.

00:21:31.190 --> 00:21:35.430
I'll continue with the rest
of the ideas that are still

00:21:35.430 --> 00:21:38.040
very common among marketers.

00:21:38.040 --> 00:21:40.610
Itamar talked about the
first one, which is brand

00:21:40.610 --> 00:21:42.570
is the most important thing.

00:21:42.570 --> 00:21:44.790
Another big one is loyalty.

00:21:44.790 --> 00:21:47.980
Talk to marketers and they
say that nurturing loyalty is

00:21:47.980 --> 00:21:51.750
the most important thing, is the
best investment you can make.

00:21:51.750 --> 00:21:54.170
Marketers love to
talk about loyalty,

00:21:54.170 --> 00:21:56.440
promote loyalty,
measure loyalty.

00:21:56.440 --> 00:21:59.920
But we're saying that when
consumers can actually

00:21:59.920 --> 00:22:03.260
assess the quality of
each individual product,

00:22:03.260 --> 00:22:06.580
loyalty is becoming
less important.

00:22:06.580 --> 00:22:09.470
Let me tell you about my
experience in buying cars

00:22:09.470 --> 00:22:11.520
throughout the '80s and '90s.

00:22:11.520 --> 00:22:13.510
So in 1985 I was a student.

00:22:13.510 --> 00:22:14.880
I got this old car.

00:22:14.880 --> 00:22:17.060
I was trying to
remember how old it was,

00:22:17.060 --> 00:22:20.180
but it was really
old, from my uncle.

00:22:20.180 --> 00:22:22.400
And I started
driving this Volvo.

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:29.310
Now in 1989, I was going to
buy a new car, or another car.

00:22:29.310 --> 00:22:32.800
The most dominant piece
of information in my mind

00:22:32.800 --> 00:22:35.550
was my past experience
with that Volvo.

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:37.140
So guess what I bought?

00:22:37.140 --> 00:22:38.400
I bought a Volvo.

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:40.950
In 1995, the same
thing happened.

00:22:40.950 --> 00:22:42.100
I bought a Volvo.

00:22:42.100 --> 00:22:45.190
In 2000, I bought
a Volvo, and so on.

00:22:45.190 --> 00:22:49.450
In 2012, I bought a new
car, and it was truly

00:22:49.450 --> 00:22:50.656
a different experience.

00:22:50.656 --> 00:22:51.780
I remember it very vividly.

00:22:51.780 --> 00:22:53.840
I was sitting in
front of my computer,

00:22:53.840 --> 00:22:57.250
cars.com, edmunds.com,
reviews from users,

00:22:57.250 --> 00:22:59.970
reviews from experts, videos.

00:22:59.970 --> 00:23:03.280
Actually, I remember one
video-- so I was still

00:23:03.280 --> 00:23:04.180
considering Volvo.

00:23:04.180 --> 00:23:07.670
It's not that I hate Volvo--
but I was looking at the video

00:23:07.670 --> 00:23:08.920
off a backup camera.

00:23:08.920 --> 00:23:11.260
You know when you put it in
reverse, you want to see.

00:23:11.260 --> 00:23:13.630
And that's a feature that
I always wanted to have.

00:23:13.630 --> 00:23:16.190
And I remember how
slowly-- I don't

00:23:16.190 --> 00:23:20.660
know if anyone here has a Volvo,
or that particular Volvo--

00:23:20.660 --> 00:23:23.380
the screen for the
backup camera was coming

00:23:23.380 --> 00:23:26.830
up so slowly that
I was saying, no.

00:23:26.830 --> 00:23:29.540
I'm not going to do that every
time that I put it in reverse,

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:32.170
and I will have to wait
for the car to back up.

00:23:32.170 --> 00:23:37.530
So suddenly, the way I
was buying this car--

00:23:37.530 --> 00:23:40.490
I was actually assessing
what it would feel like,

00:23:40.490 --> 00:23:43.580
what it would be like to
actually drive a Volvo, as

00:23:43.580 --> 00:23:46.920
opposed to relying on
some past experience.

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:53.090
So loyalty is going to
be less of an issue.

00:23:53.090 --> 00:23:58.460
Marketers can rely
less on loyalty,

00:23:58.460 --> 00:24:00.270
which means your
success is determined

00:24:00.270 --> 00:24:01.790
by your current product.

00:24:01.790 --> 00:24:04.780
The good news is
that your competitors

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:06.160
suffer from the
same thing, which

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:09.140
means that your competitive
advantage here and there can

00:24:09.140 --> 00:24:11.620
be improved.

00:24:11.620 --> 00:24:15.620
That's not new, but
as loyalty goes down,

00:24:15.620 --> 00:24:17.940
it's even more powerful.

00:24:17.940 --> 00:24:20.430
Measuring loyalty--
and there are

00:24:20.430 --> 00:24:23.460
lots of organizations
that put a lot of emphasis

00:24:23.460 --> 00:24:26.680
on measuring loyalty--
is less informative.

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:29.580
Because the consumer can
tell you that they're loyal,

00:24:29.580 --> 00:24:32.070
but when they go to
make the decision,

00:24:32.070 --> 00:24:34.760
they are not going to rely
on their past experience,

00:24:34.760 --> 00:24:38.790
but they will rely on O.

00:24:38.790 --> 00:24:43.300
The third mantra, which Itamar
essentially addressed already,

00:24:43.300 --> 00:24:46.660
but I just want to mention
again, is irrationality.

00:24:46.660 --> 00:24:50.210
So in general, marketers and
certainly people in academia

00:24:50.210 --> 00:24:52.750
believe that consumers
are irrational,

00:24:52.750 --> 00:24:57.040
and that you can manipulate
quote unquote "their action",

00:24:57.040 --> 00:25:02.220
by using the context of
offer, or the framing.

00:25:02.220 --> 00:25:04.780
Again what we're saying is, no.

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:08.960
It's going to be less true
as consumers can assess

00:25:08.960 --> 00:25:13.870
the value of each product
as Itamar just showed you.

00:25:13.870 --> 00:25:16.620
Number four is the big one--
and this is four out of six,

00:25:16.620 --> 00:25:21.050
so we're almost reaching Q&amp;A,
so think about your questions--

00:25:21.050 --> 00:25:21.960
communication.

00:25:21.960 --> 00:25:25.280
Communication is a big area, and
there are several mantras here

00:25:25.280 --> 00:25:29.670
but I've combined them under
positioning, brand awareness,

00:25:29.670 --> 00:25:31.520
persuasion are key.

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:34.760
Still marketers by and large,
if you open a textbook,

00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:37.570
they tell you that if you
persuade, if you position it

00:25:37.570 --> 00:25:41.700
rightly, target it rightly,
you will be successful.

00:25:41.700 --> 00:25:43.040
Again we're saying, no.

00:25:43.040 --> 00:25:48.040
It's going to depend much
more on the absolute value

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:48.950
of the product.

00:25:48.950 --> 00:25:50.700
That is determined by O.

00:25:50.700 --> 00:25:54.360
So let's look at something
that is called positioning.

00:25:54.360 --> 00:25:55.970
What's the idea
behind positioning?

00:25:55.970 --> 00:25:58.890
The idea is that,
if you're a company,

00:25:58.890 --> 00:26:02.940
you look for that area that has
not been occupied previously

00:26:02.940 --> 00:26:06.450
by your competitors, and you
try to associate your product

00:26:06.450 --> 00:26:06.950
with that.

00:26:06.950 --> 00:26:12.530
So Volvo stood for safety,
Cadillac stood for luxury,

00:26:12.530 --> 00:26:13.390
and so on.

00:26:13.390 --> 00:26:15.820
Which makes a lot
of sense, but this

00:26:15.820 --> 00:26:18.590
doesn't work as
well when consumers

00:26:18.590 --> 00:26:22.370
base their decisions on reviews.

00:26:22.370 --> 00:26:26.590
Let's look at an
example with phones.

00:26:26.590 --> 00:26:28.170
In the past three
or four years there

00:26:28.170 --> 00:26:32.810
have been several attempts to
position the Facebook phone.

00:26:32.810 --> 00:26:35.460
So the idea was, nobody
has the Facebook phone,

00:26:35.460 --> 00:26:38.710
so HTC and AT&amp;T,
I think, came up

00:26:38.710 --> 00:26:43.570
with this idea of associating
the product with Facebook.

00:26:43.570 --> 00:26:45.800
Maybe it's a great
idea, but the problem

00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:51.210
is that reviewers hardly
ever review a product only

00:26:51.210 --> 00:26:53.990
on one feature, especially
not the feature you

00:26:53.990 --> 00:26:56.290
decided they should
review it on.

00:26:56.290 --> 00:27:00.680
So I read a lot of reviews of
this phone, a lot of reviews,

00:27:00.680 --> 00:27:05.240
and I don't remember
maybe a handful that

00:27:05.240 --> 00:27:08.674
talked specifically a lot
about this feature of Facebook.

00:27:08.674 --> 00:27:10.590
Of course everyone
mentioned it, but they also

00:27:10.590 --> 00:27:15.157
talked about the screen,
the keyboard, voice.

00:27:15.157 --> 00:27:16.240
They talk about the phone.

00:27:16.240 --> 00:27:21.000
So it's much more difficult
to position a product the way

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:25.030
you want consumers
to think about it.

00:27:25.030 --> 00:27:28.860
Or more in general talking
about communication,

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:33.410
persuasion is becoming
much less important.

00:27:33.410 --> 00:27:35.290
There is almost
no point in trying

00:27:35.290 --> 00:27:38.150
to persuade your customer
that your product is better,

00:27:38.150 --> 00:27:40.240
because they go to O for that.

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:41.420
That's O's job.

00:27:41.420 --> 00:27:43.940
They will read
reviews and determine

00:27:43.940 --> 00:27:46.320
if your product is
better than others.

00:27:46.320 --> 00:27:47.550
So what is your job?

00:27:47.550 --> 00:27:50.890
Your job is to promote
an ongoing flow--

00:27:50.890 --> 00:27:53.280
your job as a
marketer-- is to promote

00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:57.230
an ongoing flow off authentic
content from real users,

00:27:57.230 --> 00:27:59.830
from experts, and so on.

00:27:59.830 --> 00:28:02.780
Another concept
in communication--

00:28:02.780 --> 00:28:06.520
when I worked in advertising,
it was all about awareness.

00:28:06.520 --> 00:28:10.780
You want to make the consumer
have Sony, Sony, Sony,

00:28:10.780 --> 00:28:13.350
Sony at the top of
their mind, so when

00:28:13.350 --> 00:28:15.500
they reach the
point of purchase,

00:28:15.500 --> 00:28:18.340
they'll grab the first
Sony product they see.

00:28:18.340 --> 00:28:20.000
But again, you
understand that when

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.150
the consumer comes to
a point of purchase

00:28:22.150 --> 00:28:27.870
and actually decides on reviews,
this is much less relevant.

00:28:27.870 --> 00:28:31.100
It's not about creating
that top of mind awareness.

00:28:31.100 --> 00:28:36.240
It's about generating
interest in specific products.

00:28:36.240 --> 00:28:39.300
And this translates to
very practical things.

00:28:39.300 --> 00:28:43.880
Do you go and buy banner
ads that just say Sony?

00:28:43.880 --> 00:28:46.700
Or do you create a
PR campaign, invest

00:28:46.700 --> 00:28:50.890
in a PR campaign, that promotes
the latest product that

00:28:50.890 --> 00:28:54.210
does this or that?

00:28:54.210 --> 00:28:57.120
And we talked already
about positioning

00:28:57.120 --> 00:29:02.110
that worked when people relied
on M. Much more difficult when

00:29:02.110 --> 00:29:08.170
people rely on O. There's
another mantra, or a set

00:29:08.170 --> 00:29:11.090
of mantras, in the area
of market research.

00:29:11.090 --> 00:29:13.510
Overall, marketers believe
that market research

00:29:13.510 --> 00:29:17.430
can predict people's choices.

00:29:17.430 --> 00:29:21.680
Well, it's less
true when consumers

00:29:21.680 --> 00:29:25.230
rely on O, because
here's the problem.

00:29:25.230 --> 00:29:27.420
Market research,
by and large, tries

00:29:27.420 --> 00:29:30.060
to predict what
people's preferences are

00:29:30.060 --> 00:29:31.530
at point a in time.

00:29:31.530 --> 00:29:34.470
So I ask you a lot
of questions, and I

00:29:34.470 --> 00:29:39.260
try to understand what
are your preferences.

00:29:39.260 --> 00:29:42.550
The problem is that at
point b in time, you

00:29:42.550 --> 00:29:45.380
will no longer make the decision
based on your preferences,

00:29:45.380 --> 00:29:50.160
but you will actually reach
out to O for that information.

00:29:50.160 --> 00:29:51.820
Let me give you an example.

00:29:51.820 --> 00:29:58.990
A 2007 study, conducted before
the release of the iPhone,

00:29:58.990 --> 00:30:02.340
concluded that such
convergent products are not

00:30:02.340 --> 00:30:03.830
desired by US consumers.

00:30:03.830 --> 00:30:07.780
That was a mega study
done all over the world,

00:30:07.780 --> 00:30:10.370
and they determined
the iPhone will not

00:30:10.370 --> 00:30:11.880
be desired by US consumers.

00:30:11.880 --> 00:30:14.500
As we know, this did not happen.

00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:15.640
The opposite happened.

00:30:15.640 --> 00:30:17.430
What was the problem?

00:30:17.430 --> 00:30:18.920
What was the problem here?

00:30:18.920 --> 00:30:23.120
The problem was that
they measured P. People's

00:30:23.120 --> 00:30:28.350
preferences at point a in time,
where consumers were actually

00:30:28.350 --> 00:30:34.130
influenced by O, that
is reviews, TV coverage.

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:37.170
I remember David Pogue wrote
about it in the New York Times,

00:30:37.170 --> 00:30:39.540
such an amazing review.

00:30:39.540 --> 00:30:44.160
All this stuff is the stuff
that actually influences people.

00:30:44.160 --> 00:30:47.900
So what we see in market
research-- what we already

00:30:47.900 --> 00:30:51.290
see and we predict will become
even more true-- a shift

00:30:51.290 --> 00:30:54.570
from predicting what
customers will do,

00:30:54.570 --> 00:30:57.030
to actually tracking
what are we saying.

00:30:57.030 --> 00:30:58.040
Because think about it.

00:30:58.040 --> 00:31:00.750
If O influences the
decision, go directly to O,

00:31:00.750 --> 00:31:02.190
and see what O is saying.

00:31:02.190 --> 00:31:05.690
Because this is going to
ultimately determine what

00:31:05.690 --> 00:31:07.970
the consumer will do.

00:31:07.970 --> 00:31:10.440
There will be more
systematic measurement

00:31:10.440 --> 00:31:16.560
of O and real time experiments,
adjustment and experiments,

00:31:16.560 --> 00:31:19.990
much more in real
time then trying

00:31:19.990 --> 00:31:23.700
to predict what people will do
six months from now or a year

00:31:23.700 --> 00:31:24.310
from now.

00:31:24.310 --> 00:31:27.985
Because again, they are
influenced by other sources.

00:31:30.590 --> 00:31:36.050
The last set of
mantras is in the area

00:31:36.050 --> 00:31:37.750
of diffusion of innovations.

00:31:37.750 --> 00:31:39.560
And this, I wouldn't
say that it's

00:31:39.560 --> 00:31:43.320
a mantra that is shared by the
whole tech sector, for example.

00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:45.910
I think that there are many
companies that don't really

00:31:45.910 --> 00:31:47.790
operate that way.

00:31:47.790 --> 00:31:49.640
I suspect that Google
is one of them,

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:51.320
but let's not get into that.

00:31:51.320 --> 00:31:55.440
But there are a lot of
people in high tech marketing

00:31:55.440 --> 00:31:59.060
who still believe that you
start with the early adopters,

00:31:59.060 --> 00:32:03.750
and then you try to get
into the early majority

00:32:03.750 --> 00:32:06.490
by addressing different niches.

00:32:06.490 --> 00:32:09.810
So I'm sure you're familiar
with categories of adopters.

00:32:09.810 --> 00:32:15.080
There are the innovators,
early adopters, early majority,

00:32:15.080 --> 00:32:16.900
late majority, et cetera.

00:32:16.900 --> 00:32:19.920
Well this type of
thinking-- which

00:32:19.920 --> 00:32:23.560
was initiated by Everett
Rogers, the author of "Diffusion

00:32:23.560 --> 00:32:26.590
of Innovations", who I still
consider him personally

00:32:26.590 --> 00:32:27.660
my mentor.

00:32:27.660 --> 00:32:30.920
And he also was a great
supporter of my first book

00:32:30.920 --> 00:32:33.140
that Cliff mentioned.

00:32:33.140 --> 00:32:36.820
And it's also reflective
work of a very good book

00:32:36.820 --> 00:32:39.400
called "Crossing the
Chasm" by Geoffrey Moore.

00:32:39.400 --> 00:32:41.690
I see that some people
are familiar with that.

00:32:41.690 --> 00:32:46.810
--But this way of thinking
was really true in a world

00:32:46.810 --> 00:32:51.845
where one thing existed,
and that is uncertainty.

00:32:54.550 --> 00:32:55.920
Think about it.

00:32:55.920 --> 00:32:58.470
The moment that
people can actually

00:32:58.470 --> 00:33:00.460
assess the absolute
value of things.

00:33:00.460 --> 00:33:03.280
They know what
they're getting into.

00:33:03.280 --> 00:33:07.830
Uncertainty is
resolved much faster.

00:33:07.830 --> 00:33:11.960
So there is much less of a
need for category thinking,

00:33:11.960 --> 00:33:16.970
and less of a need
for a strategy

00:33:16.970 --> 00:33:21.160
where you say, OK in order to
move to the early majority,

00:33:21.160 --> 00:33:24.130
I am going to
identify some niches

00:33:24.130 --> 00:33:26.270
and get into these niches.

00:33:26.270 --> 00:33:28.540
And if you look-- we don't
have time to get into this,

00:33:28.540 --> 00:33:29.998
but if you read it
in the book-- we

00:33:29.998 --> 00:33:33.220
talk about how the
iPad was introduced

00:33:33.220 --> 00:33:37.580
versus how the tablet
PC, back in 2000,

00:33:37.580 --> 00:33:39.050
was introduced by Microsoft.

00:33:39.050 --> 00:33:41.000
Two different approaches.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:45.120
The iPad obviously
was more successful.

00:33:45.120 --> 00:33:46.980
And one reason, we
believe, is that they

00:33:46.980 --> 00:33:51.500
let consumer niches
and different groups

00:33:51.500 --> 00:33:54.630
adopt it by themselves
without dictating

00:33:54.630 --> 00:34:00.060
which niche should buy
it according to them.

00:34:00.060 --> 00:34:02.870
So that was a very
quick overview

00:34:02.870 --> 00:34:04.240
of the different mantras.

00:34:04.240 --> 00:34:08.120
We talked about branding,
what Itamar talked about,

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:12.000
loyalty, irrationality,
communication, market research,

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:13.659
and diffusion of innovations.

00:34:13.659 --> 00:34:16.540
And more broadly, what we
talked about in this talk--

00:34:16.540 --> 00:34:20.710
and then we'll move to Q&amp;A-- we
talked about really a new era

00:34:20.710 --> 00:34:24.080
in consumer decision
making and marketing.

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:26.909
Itamar described this shift,
that we believe exists,

00:34:26.909 --> 00:34:31.699
from assessing from relative
thinking-- it's good

00:34:31.699 --> 00:34:35.719
because it's from this
brand, or from this country,

00:34:35.719 --> 00:34:40.179
or it costs so much-- to
assessing the absolute value.

00:34:40.179 --> 00:34:43.100
And what happens when
this is the case?

00:34:43.100 --> 00:34:48.860
Proxies for quality
play a much smaller role

00:34:48.860 --> 00:34:52.320
in O dependent areas.

00:34:52.320 --> 00:34:55.570
Again, the value
is determined by O.

00:34:55.570 --> 00:34:59.080
What's left for
the marketer to do?

00:34:59.080 --> 00:35:02.040
Don't fire your
marketing department yet,

00:35:02.040 --> 00:35:04.680
because marketing
is still important.

00:35:04.680 --> 00:35:07.370
Marketers have to
generate interest.

00:35:07.370 --> 00:35:12.140
They have to make sure there
is an ongoing flow of O.

00:35:12.140 --> 00:35:13.680
And probably most
important, they

00:35:13.680 --> 00:35:19.300
need to track O, analyze O, and
make sure there are adjustments

00:35:19.300 --> 00:35:23.810
to provide the best products
a company can provide.

00:35:23.810 --> 00:35:30.979
Thank you very much, and
we'll take it now for Q&amp;A.

