you're beginning to see
some websites, relatively

00:45:22.360 --> 00:45:23.850
small numbers.

00:45:23.850 --> 00:45:28.720
And they tend to be
overwhelmingly positive,

00:45:28.720 --> 00:45:31.460
which makes them a
little less useful.

00:45:34.750 --> 00:45:40.370
We would expect that
there will be development

00:45:40.370 --> 00:45:44.050
also in the b-to-b
arena with respect

00:45:44.050 --> 00:45:48.120
to their reliance on reviews.

00:45:48.120 --> 00:45:49.980
But they're beginning
from a higher level

00:45:49.980 --> 00:45:52.700
where, especially
for large purchases,

00:45:52.700 --> 00:45:58.010
they already have a pretty good
assessment of absolute value.

00:45:58.010 --> 00:45:59.840
AUDIENCE: So going
back to the first point

00:45:59.840 --> 00:46:04.360
where, if I bought something
and I really liked it--

00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:05.590
It is a very high bias.

00:46:05.590 --> 00:46:09.180
I mean, you bought Volvo
four times over the years

00:46:09.180 --> 00:46:12.700
until you changed your mind.

00:46:12.700 --> 00:46:18.080
And if the O reinforces the P,
it becomes almost automatic.

00:46:18.080 --> 00:46:18.800
It's by default.

00:46:18.800 --> 00:46:22.442
I'm going to buy this thing
that I've already tried.

00:46:22.442 --> 00:46:26.110
ITAMAR SIMONSON: Well, if you
heard good things about skim

00:46:26.110 --> 00:46:29.830
milk, and you started
buying skim milk, yeah.

00:46:29.830 --> 00:46:31.830
That becomes a
habitual purchase.

00:46:31.830 --> 00:46:34.060
That's what you're buying.

00:46:34.060 --> 00:46:35.760
You're not even
thinking about it.

00:46:35.760 --> 00:46:40.210
Many purchases, especially
more substantial ones,

00:46:40.210 --> 00:46:42.760
are not decisions that
you make every day.

00:46:42.760 --> 00:46:48.920
So when the time comes to buy
even a new electric toothbrush,

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:51.420
you may check reviews.

00:46:51.420 --> 00:46:53.570
In other words, for
less frequent decisions

00:46:53.570 --> 00:46:58.010
that tend to be the
more costly ones,

00:46:58.010 --> 00:47:01.100
that's where you see
the biggest shift.

00:47:01.100 --> 00:47:06.250
AUDIENCE: You have
mentioned that the marketers

00:47:06.250 --> 00:47:11.660
traditionally were trying to
influence consumers directly

00:47:11.660 --> 00:47:17.420
by creating a brand,
by targeting products

00:47:17.420 --> 00:47:19.090
for specific niches.

00:47:19.090 --> 00:47:22.980
And since, there is
a trend for consumers

00:47:22.980 --> 00:47:26.100
to evaluate the
value of each project

00:47:26.100 --> 00:47:31.370
individually rather than
relative to other products.

00:47:31.370 --> 00:47:34.490
So you have mentioned
that the role of marketers

00:47:34.490 --> 00:47:40.730
will be to observe
the trends in O,

00:47:40.730 --> 00:47:43.220
and then to make sure
that the company responds

00:47:43.220 --> 00:47:45.160
to those trends.

00:47:45.160 --> 00:47:48.630
So my question is
this, is it foreseeable

00:47:48.630 --> 00:47:52.800
that marketers would draw a
different lesson from this?

00:47:52.800 --> 00:47:55.560
And the lesson
would be to attempt

00:47:55.560 --> 00:47:59.650
to influence O rather
than consumers directly?

00:47:59.650 --> 00:48:04.290
And if so, what
do you think would

00:48:04.290 --> 00:48:07.714
be the effect on the
whole review system?

00:48:07.714 --> 00:48:09.130
ITAMAR SIMONSON:
Let's not forget,

00:48:09.130 --> 00:48:13.130
marketers have to come
up with good ideas.

00:48:13.130 --> 00:48:16.900
So it obviously would not
be sufficient to introduce

00:48:16.900 --> 00:48:21.845
products, see what customers
are saying, and then revise it.

00:48:24.700 --> 00:48:27.530
As Emanuel said,
market research,

00:48:27.530 --> 00:48:29.760
asking consumers what they
will want in the future,

00:48:29.760 --> 00:48:31.480
often doesn't work.

00:48:31.480 --> 00:48:35.390
For truly new concepts
it probably never did.

00:48:35.390 --> 00:48:39.720
But you need to come up
with the right products

00:48:39.720 --> 00:48:42.850
and then be responsive.

00:48:42.850 --> 00:48:43.580
Did you--

00:48:43.580 --> 00:48:44.413
EMANUEL ROSEN: Yeah.

00:48:44.413 --> 00:48:47.480
What I would like
to add-- part of it

00:48:47.480 --> 00:48:52.840
is the answer I gave this
gentleman here about marketers.

00:48:52.840 --> 00:48:54.620
Some marketers will
try to influence

00:48:54.620 --> 00:49:00.000
O in unethical ways, that
is, fake reviews, et cetera.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:01.140
So that's one part.

00:49:01.140 --> 00:49:02.940
Another part is very legitimate.

00:49:02.940 --> 00:49:08.340
That is, I think that
indeed PR, for example,

00:49:08.340 --> 00:49:10.080
is becoming more important.

00:49:10.080 --> 00:49:17.692
Because you can see PR
as a company's attempt

00:49:17.692 --> 00:49:22.200
to promote its point of view
to O. The O that matter,

00:49:22.200 --> 00:49:24.080
that is, expert reviews.

00:49:24.080 --> 00:49:27.260
The experts-- and that's
not a new thing of course,

00:49:27.260 --> 00:49:30.300
but it's becoming even
more important today

00:49:30.300 --> 00:49:34.530
when people rely so
heavily on expert reviews,

00:49:34.530 --> 00:49:40.320
and accessing these
resources is so easy.

00:49:40.320 --> 00:49:45.280
So a company that
introduces a new gadget.

00:49:45.280 --> 00:49:47.970
Today it's even more
important than 10 years ago,

00:49:47.970 --> 00:49:51.460
even five years ago, to make
sure that people who matter,

00:49:51.460 --> 00:49:56.810
the Engadgets of the world
and the tens of thousands

00:49:56.810 --> 00:49:59.820
of these bloggers, and
so on, know about it.

00:49:59.820 --> 00:50:05.180
And you cannot ultimately
influence what they will say,

00:50:05.180 --> 00:50:06.116
I would argue.

00:50:06.116 --> 00:50:07.490
Of course you can
here and there,

00:50:07.490 --> 00:50:11.880
but overall these
people, this part of O,

00:50:11.880 --> 00:50:15.640
reaches a broad consensus
about a product, which

00:50:15.640 --> 00:50:16.890
is another interesting thing.

00:50:16.890 --> 00:50:21.940
But of course trying to
influence O in legitimate ways

00:50:21.940 --> 00:50:24.220
will be important,
and also trying

00:50:24.220 --> 00:50:29.120
to make sure that there is an
ongoing flow from current users

00:50:29.120 --> 00:50:30.250
is another important thing.

00:50:30.250 --> 00:50:34.100
Because if I go to a restaurant,
or I consider a restaurant,

00:50:34.100 --> 00:50:37.510
and the last review
was written in 2009,

00:50:37.510 --> 00:50:39.480
I'm probably not going
to go there, right?

00:50:39.480 --> 00:50:43.882
So you need to make sure it's
always viable and has energy.

00:50:43.882 --> 00:50:44.840
AUDIENCE: I don't know.

00:50:44.840 --> 00:50:48.150
A company could spend
a lot of resources

00:50:48.150 --> 00:50:51.560
trying to get, say
90% of all bloggers

00:50:51.560 --> 00:50:56.737
to write about, to review,
their product first.

00:50:56.737 --> 00:50:58.820
Let's say there are two
competing companies trying

00:50:58.820 --> 00:51:02.480
to enter a certain market,
and Company A, let's say,

00:51:02.480 --> 00:51:07.190
could try to basically pay
money to all the bloggers

00:51:07.190 --> 00:51:09.270
to influence their
product first.

00:51:09.270 --> 00:51:11.980
It's not that they would
write fake reviews.

00:51:11.980 --> 00:51:13.820
They would write real
reviews, but they

00:51:13.820 --> 00:51:15.060
would write them first.

00:51:15.060 --> 00:51:17.030
So what people
see, mostly, would

00:51:17.030 --> 00:51:20.570
be reviews for product
of the Company A.

00:51:20.570 --> 00:51:25.780
Now it's not illegitimate, but
it certainly would probably

00:51:25.780 --> 00:51:30.660
influence what choices
consumers will make.

00:51:30.660 --> 00:51:32.412
EMANUEL ROSEN: In
theory-- Oh, I'm sorry--

00:51:32.412 --> 00:51:33.120
AUDIENCE: So yes.

00:51:33.120 --> 00:51:44.400
So the question is does changing
the domain where marketers

00:51:44.400 --> 00:51:54.960
try to create an influence
from consumers directly to O,

00:51:54.960 --> 00:51:57.520
do you think that benefits
the consumers overall?

00:51:57.520 --> 00:51:59.742
Does it make things
more objective?

00:51:59.742 --> 00:52:01.450
EMANUEL ROSEN: I
understand the question.

00:52:01.450 --> 00:52:03.810
Overall, there is one
thing that bloggers really

00:52:03.810 --> 00:52:07.387
want to have more
than anything else.

00:52:07.387 --> 00:52:08.220
You know what it is?

00:52:08.220 --> 00:52:09.660
Readers.

00:52:09.660 --> 00:52:14.750
So if I start feeling that this
blogger is basically giving me

00:52:14.750 --> 00:52:18.300
the party line, and are
really not giving me

00:52:18.300 --> 00:52:20.480
the true story-- Most
bloggers, if they

00:52:20.480 --> 00:52:23.756
know that there is a product
and another product will come

00:52:23.756 --> 00:52:25.630
shortly after it, the
first thing they'll do,

00:52:25.630 --> 00:52:26.860
they'll compare them.

00:52:26.860 --> 00:52:33.520
I mean bloggers want to give
their followers-- they want

00:52:33.520 --> 00:52:36.640
to have followers first of all--
and in order to have followers,

00:52:36.640 --> 00:52:42.040
they need to provide them
with valuable information.

00:52:42.040 --> 00:52:44.410
Again, the same thing that
I said about fake reviews.

00:52:44.410 --> 00:52:48.630
Yes, people will fake, will
game the system sometimes.

00:52:48.630 --> 00:52:50.350
It's far from being perfect.

00:52:50.350 --> 00:52:54.590
The same applies to the
blogosphere as to reviews.

00:52:54.590 --> 00:52:58.910
But overall, I believe
that the system does work,

00:52:58.910 --> 00:53:04.350
and blogs' reviews about
products or about services

00:53:04.350 --> 00:53:07.950
overall reflect the actual
experience of consumers.

00:53:07.950 --> 00:53:10.630
When they don't, people
will go elsewhere,

00:53:10.630 --> 00:53:12.980
because if they're
disappointed they

00:53:12.980 --> 00:53:15.110
will not trust this
source anymore.

00:53:15.110 --> 00:53:16.822
Same logic works here.

00:53:16.822 --> 00:53:18.780
ITAMAR SIMONSON: You've
been waiting patiently.

00:53:18.780 --> 00:53:19.270
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:53:19.270 --> 00:53:20.250
I have something quick.

00:53:20.250 --> 00:53:22.630
Do you see any difference
on amateur reviews

00:53:22.630 --> 00:53:26.370
like Yelp versus professional
reviews like Engadget,

00:53:26.370 --> 00:53:27.795
how they affect consumers?

00:53:31.030 --> 00:53:34.080
ITAMAR SIMONSON:
I think that they

00:53:34.080 --> 00:53:38.480
tend to talk about different
things in many cases.

00:53:38.480 --> 00:53:42.410
Let's say that I'm thinking
of buying new headphones.

00:53:42.410 --> 00:53:47.530
I'm interested in how
comfortable they are.

00:53:47.530 --> 00:53:49.580
I think for that,
I probably would

00:53:49.580 --> 00:53:52.910
go to-- if I see 100
reviews, I probably

00:53:52.910 --> 00:53:55.075
will look for user reviews.

00:53:58.225 --> 00:54:00.350
On the other hand, if you
talk about some technical

00:54:00.350 --> 00:54:04.410
specifications and comparing
this model to that model,

00:54:04.410 --> 00:54:09.794
I may rely more on
Engadget or CNET and so on.

00:54:09.794 --> 00:54:11.460
At the same time,
there is some overlap.

00:54:11.460 --> 00:54:14.480
And I think it's
not a zero sum game.

00:54:14.480 --> 00:54:19.260
You can, and consumers
as we know, they do both.

00:54:19.260 --> 00:54:23.800
They go to expert reviews,
and they go to user reviews.

00:54:23.800 --> 00:54:25.729
It's very easy to do.

